[{"id":"RF-147","entityId":"95-298","jiraId":null,"field":[{"name":"projectShortName","value":"RF"},{"name":"numberInProject","value":"147"},{"name":"summary","value":"Don't compute warnings on non-principal facts"},{"name":"description","value":"
This warning is wrong:

https://www.rootsfinder.com/tree/3543/people/4SE-0KF3-FKVN

Papa Person doesn't have a Christening event. But if you click on "Show" near the Timeline, and select "Show non-principal events", you will see that Papa Person is listed on Test Person's Christening event. But the Christening event is for Test Person, not Papa Person. The Christening fact on Papa Person has principal=false. You must ignore all facts where principal=false when calculating warnings.

I think a lot of people will not specify married name as the name type when they create a name. So to keep us from adding a lot of unnecessary warnings, I want you to check this warning only when there is a single name. If the person has more than one name, then don't check this warning.

So if there is just one name, and the name.type != "_MARNM", then check to see if the spouse has the same surname.
